'''Appen Limited''' (formerly known as Appen Butler Hill) is a publicly traded company listed on the [[Australian Securities Exchange|Australian Securities Exchange (ASX)]] under the code APX.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.asx.com.au/asx/share-price-research/company/APX|title=Share Price & Information - ASX|website=www.asx.com.au|access-date=2018-07-06}}</ref>
Appen provides or improves data used for the development of [[machine learning]] and [[artificial intelligence]] products. Data types include speech and natural language data, image and video data, text and alphanumeric data and relevance data to improve search and social media engines.<ref name=":0">{{Cite news|url=https://slator.com/financial-results/appen-outperforms-in-2017-breaks-through-billion-dollar-valuation/|title=Appen Outperforms in 2017, Breaks Through Billion Dollar Valuation {{!}} Slator|date=2018-02-23|work=Slator|access-date=2018-07-06|language=en-US}}</ref> Appen’s customers use machine learning for a variety of use cases including automatic speech recognition (ASR), computer vision, increasing conversions in [[E-commerce|eCommerce]], delivering more meaningful and personalized advertising, enhancing social media feeds or improving customer service capabilities with tools like [[Chatbot|chatbots]] and [[Virtual assistant|virtual assistants]]. <ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=u2ARWLPvnws|title=Enhancing the eCommerce Shopping Experience|last=Ireland|first=Kathy|date=May 12, 2017|work=Worldwide Business with Kathy Ireland|access-date=7/6/2018}}</ref>{{Better source|reason=primary source, the CEO about his company, not independent|date=October 2018}}
For machines to demonstrate artificial intelligence, they need to be programmed with human-quality [[Training, test, and validation sets#training set|training data]] that helps them learn.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://fairmontequities.com/is-it-time-to-buy-ai-company-appen/.|title=Is it time to buy AI company Appen? - Fairmont Equities|date=2018-04-19|work=Fairmont Equities|access-date=2018-07-06|language=en-US}}</ref> Appen uses [[crowdsourcing]] to collect and improve data and has access to a skilled crowd of over than 1,000,000 part-time contractors who collect, annotate, evaluate, label, rate, test, translate and transcribe speech, image, text and video data to turn it into effective [[Training, test, and validation sets#training set|machine learning training data]] for a variety of use cases.<ref name=":1">{{Cite news|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/forbestechcouncil/2017/05/02/how-does-a-machine-learn/#66b2e9b37441|title=How Does A Machine Learn?|last=Tan|first=Oliver|work=Forbes|access-date=2018-07-06|language=en}}</ref>{{Failed verification|date=October 2018|reason=No mention of crowdsourcing or Appen at all}}
== Locations == The company’s global headquarters is in Chatswood, New South Wales which is 10 kilometers north of the central business district of Sydney, Australia. The United States headquarters is in Kirkland Washington which is a suburb of Seattle and there are also US offices in San Francisco, California and Detroit, Michigan. Appen also has offices in Beijing, China, Davao City, Philippines, and Exeter, England.<ref name=":0" />
== Operations == At the end of 2017, revenues were AUD 166.6 million and the company had more than 350 full time employees and over 1,000,000 approved flexible workers in the Appen crowd.<ref name=":1" /> <ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.adaptiveglobalization.com/blog/2018/02/building-culture-in-language-services-companies-an-interview-with-mark-brayan-ceo-of-appen|title=Building Culture in Language Services Companies: An interview with Mark Brayan, CEO of Appen|access-date=2018-07-06|language=en}}</ref>{{Better source|reason=primary source, the CEO about his company, not independent|date=October 2018}} Tasks are performed in more than 180 languages and 130 countries.<ref name=":2">{{Cite web|url=https://www.asx.com.au/asxpdf/20180417/pdf/43t8hcq4yx8ycc.pdf|title=Appen 2017 Annual Report|last=|first=|date=April 17, 2018|website=Australian Securities Exchange (ASX)|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=July 6, 2018}}</ref>
Most of the company’s revenues are earned offshore and clients include eight of the top ten largest technology companies.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.afr.com/technology/appen-rides-the-rise-of-machine-learning-20170524-gwbu8g|title=Appen rides the rise of machine learning|date=2017-05-26|work=Financial Review|access-date=2018-07-06|language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thomsonreuters.com/en/press-releases/2018/january/thomson-reuters-names-the-worlds-top-100-technology-companies.html|title=Thomson Reuters names the world’s top 100 technology companies|access-date=2018-07-06|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.afr.com/business/small-business/midmarket-awards-finalist-preview-pronto-software-appen-itac-services-longwarry-food-park-vie-for-50100-million-category-20140811-jyqzr|title=Mid-market awards finalist preview: Pronto Software, Appen, ITAC Services, Longwarry Food Park vie for $50-$100 million category|date=2014-08-14|work=Financial Review|access-date=2018-07-06|language=en-US}}</ref>
== History == Appen was founded in Sydney in 1996 by linguist Dr. Julie Vonwiller.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.afr.com/technology/appen-shares-up-218-per-cent-in-14-months-buoyed-by-strong-results-20160228-gn61x4|title=Appen shares up 6 per cent, CEO tips search and self-driving cars as future growth drivers|date=2016-02-29|work=Financial Review|access-date=2018-07-06|language=en-US}}</ref> <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/research/stocks/private/person.asp?personId=100765170&privcapId=60270194|title=Julie Vonwiller: Executive Profile & Biography - Bloomberg|website=www.bloomberg.com|access-date=2018-07-06}}</ref> She was joined by her husband Chris Vonwiller who left his job at Telstra in 2000 to join Appen full time and is currently Non-Executive Chairman of Appen. <ref name=":2" /> <ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.afr.com/technology/profit-up-28-per-cent-at-web-search-specialist-appen-20150827-gj9cxi|title=Profit up 28 per cent at web search specialist Appen|date=2015-08-28|work=Financial Review|access-date=2018-07-06|language=en-US}}</ref>
In 2011, Appen merged with the Butler Hill Group, which was based in Ridgefield, Connecticut and Seattle, Washington and originally founded by Lisa Braden-Harder in 1993.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://quotes.wsj.com/AU/XASX/APX/company-people/executive-profile/120553142|title=APX.AU Company Profile & Executives - Appen Ltd. - Wall Street Journal|website=quotes.wsj.com|access-date=2018-07-06}}</ref> Lisa was a member of the pioneering team in grammar checking technology at the [[Thomas J. Watson|IBM T.J. Watson Research Center]] before the Butler Hill Group and stayed on as CEO until 2015. <ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.cartermorse.com/press-room/news-1/859-butler-hill-group-completes-merger-with-appen-inc|title=Butler Hill Group completes merger with Appen, Inc.|website=www.cartermorse.com|access-date=2018-07-06}}</ref> After the merger, the combined business became Appen Butler Hill and expanded its business scope to include language resources, search and text. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.linkedin.com/in/lisa-braden-harder-374624/.|title=Lisa Braden Harder|last=|first=|date=July 6, 2018|website=LinkedIn|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=July 6, 2018}}</ref>{{Better source|reason=LinkedIn is not a reliable source|date=October 2018}}
In 2012, Appen acquired Wikman Remer, a firm based in San Rafael, California, which developed tools and platforms for employee engagement, online moderation and curation.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://tmt-transactions.com/appen-and-butler-hill-merge-operations-to-create-global-leader-in-linguistic-solutions|title=Appen and Butler Hill Merge Operations To Create Global Leader in Linguistic Solutions {{!}} Technology Transactions|website=tmt-transactions.com|language=en-US|access-date=2018-07-06}}</ref>
Appen Butler Hill was re-branded as Appen in 2013, and it went public on the ASX on January 7, 2015.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.prweb.com/releases/2013/1/prweb10361091.htm|title=Introducing Social Instinct: Provider of Social Media Solutions Blends Multilingual Human Moderation with Innovative Technology|work=PRWeb|access-date=2018-07-06}}</ref>{{Better source|reason=press release|date=October 2018}}
In July of 2015 Mark Brayan joined Appen as CEO and continues to hold that position today.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.smh.com.au/business/markets/appen-off-to-a-steady-start-as-ipo-fever-continues-in-2015-20150107-12joiz.html|title=Appen off to a steady start as IPO fever continues in 2015|last=Rose|first=Sally|date=2015-01-07|website=The Sydney Morning Herald|language=en|access-date=2018-07-06}}</ref>
In October of 2016 Appen acquired a UK based transcription services company called Mendip Media Group (MMG)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.reuters.com/finance/stocks/company-officers/APX.AX|title=${Instrument_CompanyName} ${Instrument_Ric} People {{!}} Reuters.com|last=Editorial|first=Reuters|website=U.S.|language=en|access-date=2018-07-06}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.lawyersweekly.com.au/deals/19728-tech-company-acquires-transcription-service-provider|title=Tech company acquires transcription service provider|last=Bullock|first=Lara|date=2016-10-10|access-date=2018-07-06|language=en}}</ref>
Appen also acquired Leapforce in November of 2017 for U.S. $80M, adding additional capabilities in search relevance and growing its crowd to over 1,000,000 flexible workers.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.finnewsnetwork.com.au/archives/finance_news_network124534.html|title=Appen announcse strategic UK acquisition|date=2016-10-03|work=Finance News Network|access-date=2018-07-06|language=en}}</ref> <ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.finnewsnetwork.com.au/archives/finance_news_network168042.html|title=Appen to acquire new acquisitions for US$80m|date=2017-11-29|work=Finance News Network|access-date=2018-07-06|language=en}}</ref>
