'''Henry Norris Churton''' (15 January 1843 – 20 January 1904) was an [[Anglican]] [[Colonialism|colonial]] [[bishop]] in the 20th century.<ref>[http://bahamas.anglican.org/history.php Diocesan history]</ref>

Churton was born in 1843 into an ecclesiastical family, the son of [[Edward Churton]], [[Archdeacon of Cleveland]].<ref>''[[Who's Who|Who was Who 1987-1990]]'': London, [[A & C Black]], 1991 {{ISBN|0-7136-3457-X}}</ref> He was educated at [[Eton College|Eton]] and [[University College, Oxford]]; and ordained in 1868.<ref>"The Clergy List, Clerical Guide and Ecclesiastical Directory" London, Hamilton & Co 1889</ref> His first posts were [[Curate|curacies]] at [[Stoke-on-Trent]] and [[East Retford]]. From 1872 to 1879 he was Vicar of St John Evangelist, [[West Bromwich]] then [[Perpetual curate|Perpetual Curate]] of St James’ Chapel, [[Avonwick]].<ref>[http://www.cornishsurname.matthewcornish.info/articles/132.htm Details of church]</ref> Later he was [[Archdeacon]] of the [[Bahamas]] before being ordained to the [[episcopate]] in 1902, succeeding his elder brother ([[Edward Churton (bishop)|Edward]]) as [[Bishop of Nassau]].<ref>[http://www.stagnesgt.com/anglican_diocese/3072.html Anglican church in the Bahamas] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110215094055/http://www.stagnesgt.com/anglican_diocese/3072.html |date=2011-02-15 }}</ref> He was consecrated [[Bishop (Anglicanism)|bishop]] by the Archbishop of Canterbury at [[St Paul's Cathedral]] on 13 July 1902.<ref>{{Cite newspaper The Times |articlename=Ecclesiastical intelligence |day_of_week=Tuesday |date=15 July 1902 |page_number=7 |issue=36820| }}</ref> He had previously received the honorary degree [[Doctor of Divinity]] (DD) from the [[University of Oxford]] in May 1902.<ref>{{Cite newspaper The Times |articlename=University intelligence |day_of_week=Wednesday |date=28 May 1902 |page_number=12 |issue=36779| }}</ref>

He died in a yachting accident on 20 January 1904.<ref>'' Mentioned in the obituary of his elder brother [[Edward Churton (bishop)|Bishop Edward Churton]] [[The Times]]  Friday, May 24, 1912; pg. 59; Issue 39907; col C</ref>

