{{no footnotes|date=February 2013}} {{Spanish name|Sampedro|Cameán}} {{Infobox person | name = Ramón Sampedro | image = Placa homenaje a Sampedro en As Furnas 2.jpg | image_size = 220px | alt = | caption = | birth_name = Ramón Sampedro Cameán | birth_date = {{Birth date|1943|01|05}} | birth_place = [[Porto do Son]], [[Galicia (Spain)|Galicia]], [[Spain]] | death_date = {{Death date and age|1998|01|12|1943|01|05}} | death_place = [[Boiro]], Galicia, Spain | death_cause = Assisted suicide | nationality = Spanish | occupation = Seaman | known_for = Right-to-die case | signature = }} '''Ramón Sampedro Cameán''' (5 January 1943 – 12 January 1998) was a Spanish seaman and writer. Sampedro became a [[quadriplegic]] at the age of 25 (23 August 1968), following a diving accident, and fought for his right to an [[assisted suicide]] for the next 29 years.
==Demand for suicide== [[File:Lugar del accidente de Ramón Sampedro en As Furnas 1.jpg|thumb|Place in As Furnas where Ramón Sampedro jumped into.]] As a young man he jumped into the sea from rocks near his home, a fishing village in the northern Spanish region of Galicia.<ref name=Usher>{{cite journal |url=http://www.time.com/time/magazine/1998/int/980126/file.live_and_let_die.sh11.html |magazine=[[Time (magazine)|Time]] |title=Live and Let Die |date=January 26, 1998 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110628230407/http://www.time.com/time/magazine/1998/int/980126/file.live_and_let_die.sh11.html |archive-date=June 28, 2011 |last=Usher |first=Rod |author-link=Rod Usher |volume=151 |issue=4}}</ref> Misjudging the water's depth, he struck his head on the bottom.<ref name=Usher/> He sustained a complete spinal cord injury, leaving him paralyzed from the neck down.<ref name=Usher/>
Sampedro tried Spain's lower courts, its higher courts, and even the [[European Commission]] on [[Human Rights]] in [[Strasbourg]] to end his life.<ref name=Usher/> His argument hinged on the fact that he was sure of his decision to die. However, owing to his paralysis, he was physically unable to commit [[suicide]] without help. He argued that suicide was a right that he was being denied, and he sought legal advice concerning his right to receive assistance to end his life, first in the courts of Spain, where his case attracted country-wide attention. Eventually, his fight became known worldwide.
== Death and aftermath == [[File:Placa homenaje a Sampedro en As Furnas 3.jpg|thumb|[[Commemorative plaque]] for Sampedro in As Furnas.]] Sampedro died on Monday 12 January 1998 in [[Boiro]], Spain, from [[potassium cyanide]] poisoning.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1998/03/09/world/a-suicide-tape-on-tv-inflames-the-issue-in-spain.html |newspaper=[[The New York Times]] |title=A Suicide Tape on TV Inflames the Issue in Spain |date=March 9, 1998 |access-date=February 26, 2013 |publisher=[[The New York Times Company]]}}</ref> Several days later, a close friend of Sampedro, Ramona Maneiro, was arrested and charged with assisting his suicide. Sampedro had divided the elements required to complete his suicide into individual tasks, each small enough that no single person could be convicted of assisting the suicide process entirely. Maneiro was released due to lack of evidence. No further charges were ever filed in connection with Sampedro's death.
Seven years later, after the [[statute of limitations]] had expired, Maneiro, speaking on a [[Spanish language|Spanish]] [[talk show]], admitted to providing Sampedro with a cyanide-laced drink and a straw. She said "I did it for love." She also said she had turned on the video camera that recorded Sampedro's last words before he drank the poison and that she was in the room, behind the camera.
He left an open letter to the judges and the society and caused an ethical turmoil in the Spanish society which led to a Senatorial Committee on Euthanasia in 1999.
== In popular culture == The story of Sampedro's life and death was made into a Spanish [[film]], ''[[Mar adentro]]'' (2004), directed by [[Alejandro Amenábar]],<ref>{{cite news |author=EP |title=Amenábar llevará al cine la vida del tetrapléjico Ramón Sampedro |url=http://www.diariodeleon.es/noticias/cultura/amenabar-llevara-cine-vida-tetraplejico-ramon-sampedro_84976.html |date=June 4, 2003 |access-date=April 17, 2018 |newspaper=Diario de León |language=es |location=Madrid}}</ref> in which he was portrayed by [[Javier Bardem]].<ref>{{cite news |author=Agencias |title=Javier Bardem interpretará al tetrapléjico Ramón Sampedro en la próxima película de Amenabar |url=https://elpais.com/cultura/2003/06/03/actualidad/1054591204_850215.html |date=June 3, 2003 |access-date=April 17, 2018 |newspaper=[[El País]] |language=es |location=Madrid}}</ref> The movie drew international attention and won the [[Academy Award for Best Foreign Language Film|Best Foreign Language Film]] at the [[77th Academy Awards]].<ref>{{cite news |author=Agencias |title='Mar adentro' consigue el Oscar a la Mejor Película de habla no inglesa |url=https://elpais.com/cultura/2005/02/28/actualidad/1109545201_850215.html |date=February 28, 2005 |access-date=April 17, 2018 |newspaper=[[El País]] |language=es |location=Madrid}}</ref>
Sampredo wrote a book before he died, titled ''Cartas desde el infierno''.<ref>{{cite news |title=La resurrección literaria del gallego Ramón Sampedro |url=http://www.elmundo.es/elmundolibro/2004/10/01/protagonistas/1096629518.html |date=October 1, 2004 |access-date=April 17, 2018 |newspaper=[[El Mundo (Spain)|El Mundo]] |language=es |location=Madrid |publisher=Mundinteractivos, [[Sociedad Anónima|S.A.]]}}</ref> It includes a collection of poems, short essays, and reflections on life from Sampedro’s point of view. After the release of ''Mar adentro'', it was edited again.<ref>{{cite news |title=El libro de Ramón Sampedro «Cartas desde el infierno» vuelve a editarse |url=http://www.abc.es/hemeroteca/historico-29-09-2004/abc/Cultura/el-libro-de-ramon-sampedro-cartas-desde-el-infierno-vuelve-a-editarse_9623891387040.html# |date=September 29, 2004 |access-date=April 17, 2018 |newspaper=[[ABC (Spain)|ABC]] |language=es}}</ref> {{As of|2005}}, the book was sold 100.000 times.<ref>{{cite news |author=M. L. |title=«Cartas desde el infierno», de Ramón Sampedro, supera los 100.000 ejemplares vendidos |url=https://www.lavozdegalicia.es/noticia/television/2005/01/19/cartas-infierno-ramon-sampedro-supera-100000-ejemplares-vendidos/0003_3384296.htm |date=January 19, 2005 |access-date=April 17, 2018 |newspaper=[[La Voz de Galicia]] |language=es |location=Madrid}}</ref>
Spanish singer-songwriter [[Andres Suarez]] wrote a song inspired by Sampedro's life, titled "Marinero," which was included in his 2007 album [[Maneras de romper una ola]].
