'''Sir Thomas Browne''' (1402{{spaced ndash}}20 July 1460) was a [[Member of Parliament]] and [[Chancellor of the Exchequer]]. He was beheaded for treason on 20 July 1460.

==Career==
Thomas Browne was born in 1402, the son and heir of Sir Robert Browne of [[Betchworth]] and a nephew of Stephen Browne MP.<ref>History of Parliament...: 1439-1509By Josiah Clement Wedgwood, Anne Holt</ref> He was sworn to the peace in [[Kent]] in 1434.{{citation needed|date=September 2013}} He was [[Justice of Peace]] for Kent from 1436 to 24 December 1450.{{citation needed|date=September 2013}} He was [[High Sheriff of Kent]] in 1439 and [[Member of Parliament]] for [[Dover (UK Parliament constituency)|Dover]] in the same year, and [[Knight of the Shire]] for [[Kent (UK Parliament constituency)|Kent]] in 1445.{{sfn|Richardson I|2011|p=338}} He was present at Parliament in 1447 and 1449 as Under Treasurer.{{citation needed|date=September 2013}} He was MP between 1449 and 1450 for [[Wallingford (UK Parliament constituency)|Wallingford]].{{citation needed|date=September 2013}}

He served as [[Treasurer of the Household]] to [[Henry VI of England|Henry VI]].{{sfn|Richardson I|2011|p=338}} He was knighted 1449/1451.{{citation needed|date=September 2013}} During the reign of King [[Henry VI of England|Henry VI]], his highest post was that of [[Chancellor of the Exchequer]], which he held between 1440 and 1450.{{citation needed|date=September 2013}} He was later Justice of Peace for [[Surrey]] from 20 July 1454 till his death.{{citation needed|date=September 2013}}

Browne was convicted of treason on 20 July 1460, and immediately executed. According to some sources he was beheaded, {{sfn|Richardson I|2011|p=338}} while according to other sources he and six others were executed at [[Tyburn]].{{citation needed|date=September 2013}}

==Property==
*[[Betchworth Castle]], which Browne purchased from his father in law, [[Thomas FitzAlan]].
*Tonford Manor, [[Thanington Without|Thanington]], Kent, called 'Toniford', 'Tunford' etc., which came to him from [[Thomas Fogge|Sir Thomas Fogge]], (died anno 9 Henry IV) through the Brownes, who in the 27th year of Henry VI obtained a grant of liberty to embattle and impark and to have free warren etc. within this manor.
*Morris-Court, [[Bapchild]], Kent, situated within the ecclesiastical jurisdiction of the [[diocese of Rochester]] and deanery of [[Sittingbourne]].
*Eythorne Manor, Kent. Browne obtained the grant of a fair at the neighbouring village of Wimlingswold, to be held on the feast of St. Margaret the Virgin (20 July), but which is now held yearly on Old May-day.
*Hoptons Manor in the parish of [[Alkham]], Kent.
*Kingsnorth Manor, [[Ulcombe]], Kent. In the 27th year of the reign of Henry VI, Browne obtained licence for a fair in this parish on the feast of St. Michael, and that same year had licence to embattle his mansion there and to enclose a park, and for freewarren in all his demesne lands within the manor.
*Westbury Manor, [[Wateringbury]], Kent, which Browne purchased from Richard Fishborne in the 33d year of Henry VI's reign. Now called Manor Farm.
*Swanscombe Manor, [[Greenhithe]], Kent.
*Tong Castle and Manor, [[Tonge, Kent|Tong, Kent]], which had been in possession of [[Richard of York, 3rd Duke of York|Richard, Duke of York]], but was taken by the crown in anno 38 Henry VI,<ref>{{cite journal |last=Hasted |first=Edward |year=1798 |title=Parishes |url=http://www.british-history.ac.uk/report.aspx?compid=62954 |journal=The History and Topographical Survey of the County of Kent |publisher=Institute of Historical Research |volume=6 |pages=132–143 |accessdate=3 April 2014}}</ref> and granted to Browne prior to his being knighted and appointed comptroller and treasurer of the King's household. Browne soon afterwards obtained a grant of a fair at this manor on St. James's day yearly, and another for liberty to embattle his mansion and to impark his lands here.
*The manor of [[Barfreston]], Kent<ref>{{Cite journal |last=Hasted |first=Edward |year=1800 |title=Parishes |url=http://www.british-history.ac.uk/report.aspx?compid=62986 |journal=The History and Topographical Survey of the County of Kent |publisher=Institute of Historical Research |volume=10 |pages=71–78 |accessdate=11 February 2014}}</ref>

==Family==
In about 1437, Browne married Eleanor FitzAlan, daughter of [[Thomas Fitzalan|Sir Thomas FitzAlan]], third son of [[John FitzAlan, 2nd Baron Arundel]] (d. 14 August 1390), and [[Elizabeth le Despenser]] (d. 10 or 11 April 1408), by whom he had seven sons and two daughters:{{sfn|Cokayne|1910|p=260}}{{sfn|Richardson I|2011|pp=32-3, 338}}
*William Browne{{sfn|Richardson I|2011|p=338}} (of Tavistock, Devon).{{citation needed|date=September 2013}}
*[[George Browne (died 1483)|Sir George Browne]], beheaded in 1483.{{sfn|Richardson I|2011|p=338}} His estates were confiscated, but were afterwards restored to his heirs in 1485 by Henry VII.<ref>[http://www.british-history.ac.uk/report.aspx?compid=62953 'Parishes: Bapchild', The History and Topographical Survey of the County of Kent: Volume 6 (1798), pp. 122-132] Retrieved 23 September 2013.</ref>
*Thomas Browne.{{sfn|Richardson I|2011|p=338}}
*[[Sir Anthony Browne (d.1506)|Sir Anthony Browne]].{{sfn|Richardson I|2011|p=338}}
*Robert Browne, esquire,{{sfn|Richardson I|2011|p=338}} of [[Luddenham, Kent]], Comptroller of the Household to [[Thomas FitzAlan, 17th Earl of Arundel]], who married a wife named Anne, by whom he had a daughter, Eleanor Browne, who married firstly, before 9 December 1509, Thomas Fogge (d. 16 August 1512), esquire, sergeant porter of [[Calais]], younger son of [[John Fogge|Sir John Fogge]], and secondly Sir William Kempe (d. 28 January 1539) of [[Olantigh]], [[Kent]].{{sfn|Richardson III|2011|p=275}}{{sfn|Philipott|1876|pp=178, 351}}{{sfn|Hitchin-Kemp|1902|pp=24-5}}{{sfn|Smith|1859|pp=108-9}}
*Leonard Browne.{{sfn|Richardson I|2011|p=338}}
*Edward Browne.{{sfn|Richardson I|2011|p=338}}
*Catherine Browne, who married Humphrey Sackville, of [[Buckhurst Park, Sussex]] (1426 – 24 January 1488),{{sfn|Richardson I|2011|p=338}} son of Sir Edward Sackville and his wife Margaret Wakehurst.<ref>{{cite|page = 540|article = Poyntz of Cowdray Park|title = A Genealogical and Heraldic History of the Commoners of Great Britain and Ireland Enjoying Territorial Possessions or High Official Rank, but Uninvested with Heritable Honours|volume = 3|first = John|last = Burke|access-date = 7 December 2016|url = https://books.google.fr/books?id=upFIAQAAMAAJ&dq=buckhurst++humphrey+sackville&hl=fr&source=gbs_navlinks_s|publisher = Colburn|location = London|year = 1836}}</ref>
*Jane Browne.{{citation needed|date=September 2013}}

